                            <h2>Airline policy when we travel with a pet</h2>
                            <p>When it comes to getting a flight with your furry friend, different airlines have policies and regulations that may differ depending on the kind of airline, where you're headed, and what animal you have. Here are some generally known features of airline pet policies that are provided by FaresMatch:</p>
                            <ul>
                                <li>Cabin travel is mostly permitted for small pets (usually dogs, cats, and sometimes little rabbits) if their owners present them in special carriers that can fit underneath any seat.</li>
                                <li>If the animal is huge or doesn't meet the requirements for being in the cabin, then it will likely have to be put in the cargo hold. The animals should be placed inside durable cages that are in accordance with what each airline requires when taking animals.</li>
                                <li>Service animals like service dogs are usually accepted by most airlines without charging extra fees. You may need to provide some sort of paperwork that shows this particular animal is indeed certified as a service animal.</li>
                                <li>Most airlines require a health certificate showing that your dog or cat has been seen by a veterinarian within a specified number of days before leaving (usually 10). You may also need vaccination cards, for example, against rabies.</li>
                                <li>A few airlines have limitations regarding certain breeds, most notably brachycephalic (short-nosed), due to their likelihood of experiencing respiratory problems during flights.</li>
                            </ul>

                            <p>For compliance reasons, it’s important to always check individual pet policies with an airline before leaving for your trip dates.</p>

